    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "It was noticed that when 'showcmd' is enabled, even completed commands (or trivial commands such as `j` or ESC) cause a screen update, which is then cleared by an immediate redraw.\r\n\r\n- RPC: `nvim_input('<esc>')` \r\n- One of the updates is: `#(\"cursor_goto\" #(9 21)) #(\"put\" #(\"^\") #(\"[\")) #(\"cursor_goto\" #(0 0)))`\r\n\r\nSometimes you can even see this in a slow terminal, by holding down `j`, for example.\r\n\r\nPerhaps we can avoid the screen update entirely.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I looked into the code when working on #7466, to me the \"root cause\" is that it sidesteps the ordinary screen redraw logic, and draws directly on the screen with `screen_puts`. Instead, it should just manage the `showcmd_buf` and set some flag similar to `redraw_later()`. And the actual redraw code in `screen.c` should then redraw the showcmd.",
